{
  "query": "What are the benefits and harms of using acoustic devices on fishing gear in coastal waters to protect porpoises?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on 33 studies evaluating acoustic devices on fishing gear, the benefits include significant reductions in porpoise entanglements and behavior modifications that help protect marine mammals. Nine studies found that acoustic devices on cod traps or fishing nets resulted in fewer entanglements of harbour porpoises, Franciscana dolphins, beaked whales and small cetaceans (Action 2808). Twelve of 16 controlled studies found that acoustic devices on fishing nets, float lines or simulated fishing nets resulted in harbour porpoises, common bottlenose dolphins, tuxuci dolphins, finless porpoises and seals approaching nets less closely, having fewer encounters or interactions with nets, or reduced activity and sightings in surrounding areas (Action 2808). One controlled study found that fishing nets with a 'complete' set of acoustic devices had fewer harbour porpoise entanglements, but those with an 'incomplete' set did not (Action 2808). One study found that acoustic devices reduced harbour porpoise entanglements in one fishing area but not another (Action 2808).\n\nHowever, there are limitations and potential harms. Four studies found that acoustic devices on trawl nets, float lines or simulated fishing nets did not have significant effects on the behaviour of common bottlenose dolphins, harbour porpoises, Indo-Pacific humpback dolphins or dugongs (Action 2808). Three studies found that acoustic devices resulted in fewer entanglements of some species but not others (Action 2808). Some studies showed mixed results with distance effects decreasing after initial exposure, as one study found killer whales were recorded further from fishing vessels when acoustic devices were used during hauls, but distances decreased after the first exposure to the device (Action 2815). Additionally, acoustic devices reduced surfacing, echolocation rates, and time spent foraging or socializing of Indo-Pacific humpback dolphins and Australian snubfin dolphins (Action 2815).",
