tools_called.args:
{"query": "In the South Pacific and Indian Oceans, what is the best available method for shark control programs to minimize harm to non-target marine mammals?", "summary": "Based on studies conducted in the South Pacific and Indian Oceans, using baited lines instead of nets for shark control is identified as the best available method to minimize harm to non-target marine mammals (Action 2856). Two site comparison studies in the Indian Ocean (South Africa) and South Pacific Ocean (Australia) found that baited lines used for shark control had fewer entanglements of dolphins, whales and dugongs than nets. Additionally, one study in the South Pacific Ocean found that using baited lines instead of nets increased the survival of entangled common and bottlenose dolphins (Action 2856).

Catch and hook protection devices also show effectiveness in these regions (Action 2821). Studies in the South Pacific Ocean (Chile, Australia and Fiji) and Indian Ocean (Seychelles, Madagascar) found that using cage or chain devices on fishing hooks resulted in fewer unwanted catches of toothed whales, and that net sleeves or cage and chain devices on fishing hooks reduced damage to fish catches by sperm whales, killer whales and toothed whales.

Acoustically reflective fishing gear materials provide another option (Action 2807), though evidence is limited for these specific ocean regions. Two of three controlled studies found that fishing nets made from acoustically reflective materials (iron-oxide or barium sulfate) had fewer entanglements of harbour porpoises than conventional fishing nets, though one study found that nets made from barium sulfate did not reduce dolphin entanglements.", "action_ids": ["2856","2821","2807"]}

