{"query": "What are the available strategies to reduce the negative impacts of aquaculture systems on marine mammals?", "summary": "Based on the action documents reviewed, several strategies are available to reduce the negative impacts of aquaculture systems on marine mammals. The most extensively studied strategy is the use of acoustic devices at aquaculture systems (Action 2775), where six studies found that four of six studies showed acoustic devices reduced predation on caged salmon by grey seals, harbour seals and South American sea lions, or reduced the number of harbour seals approaching fish cages, while two studies found acoustic devices did not reduce harbour seal predation or reduce the presence of common bottlenose dolphins around fin-fish farms. 

Another strategy with some evidence is replacing or repairing damaged anti-predator nets around aquaculture systems (Action 2774), where one study in the North Atlantic Ocean found that replacing anti-predator nets more frequently at salmon farms resulted in fewer salmon losses to harbour seal predation.

Additional strategies identified include: introducing and enforcing regulations to prevent the use of harmful deterrents on mammals at aquaculture systems (Action 2746); modifying anti-predator nets around aquaculture systems (Action 2743); modifying aquaculture gear (Action 2742); minimizing food waste at aquaculture systems (Action 2744); reducing the amount of antibiotics used in aquaculture systems (Action 2878); introducing and enforcing water quality regulations for aquaculture systems (Action 2876); and using non-toxic antifouling coatings on surfaces (Action 2908). However, no studies were found that evaluated the effectiveness of these latter strategies.", "action_ids": ["2775","2774","2746","2743","2742","2744","2878","2876","2908"]}

