{"query": "For shark control programs in Australia and South Africa, what is the evidence for alternative methods to nets that reduce harm to marine mammals?", "summary": "Evidence for alternative methods to shark nets that reduce harm to marine mammals comes from studies in Australia and South Africa. Using baited lines instead of nets for shark control shows significant benefits: two site comparison studies in the Indian Ocean (South Africa) and South Pacific Ocean (Australia) found that baited lines had fewer entanglements of dolphins, whales and dugongs than nets (Action 2856). Additionally, one study in the South Pacific Ocean found that using baited lines instead of nets increased the survival of entangled common and bottlenose dolphins (Action 2856).

Other alternative methods include installing exclusion and/or escape devices on fishing nets. Studies in the Indian Ocean (Australia, Tasmania) and Tasman Sea (Tasmania) demonstrate that these devices can reduce marine mammal entanglements: three studies found that installing exclusion and/or escape devices on trawl nets reduced the number of trapped or entangled Antarctic fur seals and common bottlenose dolphins, and one before-and-after study found that these devices reduced common bottlenose dolphin entanglements for three of four fishing vessels (Action 2823).

Acoustic devices on fishing gear represent another alternative approach. Multiple studies including those in Moreton Bay (Australia), Rainbow Channel (Australia), and Indian Ocean (Australia) found that acoustic devices resulted in fewer entanglements or reduced interactions with nets for harbour porpoises, common bottlenose dolphins, and other marine mammals (Action 2808). Nine studies found that acoustic devices on fishing nets resulted in fewer entanglements of harbour porpoises, Franciscana dolphins, beaked whales and small cetaceans (Action 2808).", "action_ids": ["2856","2823","2808"]}

