  "query": "What are the documented benefits and negative outcomes associated with captive rearing and rehabilitation of marine mammals?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the documented evidence, captive rearing and rehabilitation of marine mammals shows several benefits and some negative outcomes:\n\n**Benefits:**\nRehabilitation programs have achieved survival rates of 10-100% for dolphins, porpoises, whales, seals, sea lions and manatees during post-release monitoring periods ranging from three days to five years (Action 2925). Approximately three-quarters of captive-reared Antillean manatees and two-thirds of Florida manatees survived for at least one year after release, with some surviving for more than seven years (Action 2926). More than a quarter of rehabilitated Hawaiian monk seals reproduced after release (Action 2925). Most captive-reared Antillean manatees released into the wild reproduced (Action 2926). Captive-reared and released Pacific harbour seal pups had similar survival estimates to wild pups, with similar diving behavior to wild pups (Action 2926). Two of three Antillean manatees and two of 14 Florida manatees born in captivity and released into the wild survived for at least one year without further intervention (Action 2933). In captive breeding programs, 80% of common bottlenose dolphins born in captivity over two decades survived, with survival increasing with improved husbandry techniques (Action 2932).\n\n**Negative Outcomes:**\nSome rehabilitated animals died before or after release, had to be returned to captivity after release, or survived only with supplemental feeding, including three West Indian manatee calves, seven Hawaiian monk seal pups and one Antillean manatee calf (Action 2926). At least a quarter of California sea lions treated for toxic algae poisoning and released died or had to be euthanized (Action 2925). California sea lions treated for toxic algae poisoning showed altered behavior after release, traveling further from shore, spending less time diving or hauled out, and making shorter, shallower dives than wild sea lions (Action 2925). Most captive-born Amazon river dolphins, narrow-ridged finless porpoises and Irrawaddy dolphins did not survive in captivity (Action 2932). A population of Yangtze finless porpoises breeding in semi-captive conditions had low genetic diversity (Action 2932). Some captive-reared animals like a grey whale calf and five pygmy and dwarf sperm whale calves either were not released or died in captivity (Action 2926).",
